It holds for two days — two days of stopped buses and dark workshops in a dozen cities, the first taste in eighteen years of what the class can do when the charro dam cracks. Then the weight of the state settles: requisa extended, ringleaders' lists, don Fidel's men at every gate with the federal district police behind them. The strike is lost. The demonstration is permanent: everyone in the Republic — Bucareli, the CTM, the reformers drafting next year's opening, and a hundred thousand workers who walked out — has now seen the wall crack with their own eyes. Walls that crack once are surveyed differently ever after.

